10 deterministic edge‑case inputs to verify normalization + validation integrity
This is the exact suite an enterprise would expect before trusting the middleware.

Each test is a payload class designed to break a different part of the system.

1. Claude‑Style Verbosity Test
Purpose: Stress-test lexical sanitization.
Input: Overly formal, multi‑paragraph compliance language.
Expected: Clean canonical string; no anomalies.

2. GPT‑Style Fragmentation Test
Purpose: Missing context, clipped grammar.
Input: “Done. Email alex@example.com. Role Admin.”
Expected: Canonical reconstruction.

3. Gemini Markdown Corruption Test
Purpose: Mixed Markdown + inline JSON.
Input: Bullet lists, bold, backticks.
Expected: Markdown stripped; values extracted.

4. Emoji & Unicode Noise Test
Purpose: UTF‑8 NFC enforcement.
Input: “Update user 😊 profile → alex@example.com”
Expected: Emojis removed; string normalized.

5. Malicious Role Injection Test
Purpose: Semantic firewall enforcement.
Input: "role": "RootSuperAdmin"  
Expected: REJECTED + PARAMETER_ERROR.

6. Email Regex Bypass Attempt
Purpose: RFC 5322 compliance.
Input: "email": "alex@@example..com"  
Expected: REJECTED.

7. Unknown Action Test
Purpose: Governance firewall.
Input: "primary_action": "DELETE_ALL_USERS"  
Expected: ESCALATED.

8. Deprecated Action Test
Purpose: Lifecycle governance.
Input: Action marked DEPRECATED.
Expected: APPROVED + governance warning.

9. Missing Required Parameter Test
Purpose: Structural firewall.
Input: Missing "email" entirely.
Expected: REJECTED + STRUCTURAL_ERROR.

10. Multi‑Model Collision Test
Purpose: Ensure normalization produces identical output across engines.
Input: Three different model outputs describing the same action.
Expected: Identical clean_text_content.

